Branson, Missouri 
Nov. 28-1920
My Dear little girl:
Much more time has elapsed than I Expected, since I saw you, before writing, But so many things have happened in such a short time, that I have been really dizzy your sweet face comes to me so many times and especially as I saw you <unclear/> the train. And now I am beginning to realize how far I am from you all. 
Letters from my girls make me feel that I maybe have been heartless in coming so far. But I needed a change and surely this is a change
we are going to have a chickens <unclear/> we have the finest Cistern full of soft water. Our Well is 103 feet deep and very good water tho not quite so good as our water athome. We all like the county and now be sure when you name your honey moon <del>tip</del> trip be sure you make it Brnaons and we will show you a good time. Mona is sick tonight I was sick the first of the week we both over worked packing and moving in Bancroft and now we are getting results. While me you dear girl; and remember me to your folks. I shall try to write you more of a letter the next time I had a letter for recorded to me here from Mrs. Preston they did not know we were moved. I must write her. Tell me all the news and remeber I miss you! love <unclear/> M. Neihardt

